        "about_eng": "Parantaka Viranarayanan ruled the Pandya kingdom during a period when the Chola dynasty was steadily rising in power, presenting significant challenges to regional stability. He devoted much of his reign to defending Pandya lands against external threats, particularly from the expanding Chola forces. This period was marked by continuous military pressure, making his rule a time of strategic vigilance and defensive campaigns. Despite these challenges, he managed to maintain a degree of independence and safeguard Pandya authority, albeit only briefly. Over time, the increasing influence and aggression of the Cholas began to encroach upon Pandya territories, signaling the growing dominance of the neighboring empire. His reign thus reflects the struggles of a smaller kingdom striving to preserve its sovereignty amid the rise of a powerful adversary."
